    "updated_at": "2017-06-20T16:16:20Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Think of this analogy: dynamically-loaded libraries should not (and probably cannot) verify that you have pushed the right arguments into the stack before calling them. They just expose their ABI as header files and (unless you are writing assembly by hand) any high-level language compiler worth its salt will take care of the rest. What the library code SHOULD do is try to make sense of the arguments assuming they were pushed the right way, or bail out if not.",
